title: For Sale:  Glock 35 Gen3 Cal .40 S&W ** Layaway Available **
postcontent: Glock 35 Gen3 Cal .40 S&W ** Layaway Available **Condition: Used ( The Gun comes in Original Hard Case with Paperwork )Stock Number: G-22454-1Price: $600Glock Perfection. The Glock 35 Gen3 is ideal for home defense, concealed carry or as a duty weapon. It is a tactical size, .40S/W, polymer frame handgun that uses a locked breach system referred to as "Safe Action". This is the combination of a trigger safety, firing pin safety and drop safety that render the loaded pistol incapable of firing, even when banged or bumped, unless someone actually squeezes the trigger. Because it does not have a hammer, the spring loaded striker (firing pin) is technically blocked off, partially retracted and not in geometric alignment with a chambered cartridge. It is only by squeezing the trigger, which fully retracts and then releases the striker, that makes the pistol then capable of firing. The absence of a hammer also provides a sleeker profile that reduces both size and weight, while optimizing a smoother draw from concealment. Manufacturer: GlockModel: 35 Gen3Caliber: .40 S&WCapacity: 15Barrel: 5.5"

title: For Sale/Trade:  Barreled Action project - Prewar Arisaka Type 38 Koishikawa Arsenal (Tokyo)
postcontent: Barreled action from an Arisaka Type 38 bolt-action rifle in 6.5x50 caliber. Mum is ground. Includes front and rear sights.Serial number 20XXX indicates it was manufactured at the Koishikawa Arsenal in Tokyo prior to 1935. The low serial number suggests it's closer to WWI than WWII vintage. This rifle is also marked as being transfered to a school, so it was likely used to train students prior to WWII (Starting in the 1920s, all Junior and Senior high school boys in Japan were required to take military training). This is NOT a blank or dummy rifle sometimes found at schools, it is a full military production receiver with rifled barrel capable of firing live ammo. These were sometimes re-activated for military use as needed. The metal has an aged patina where exposed, and is bright where it was under the stock and handguard.The bore and rifling looks ok, but I am not an expert. $50 or trade for ammo, looking for various calibers.

title: For Sale:  Schmidt-Rubin 1911 Carbine (K11) & M1899 Bayonet
location: Long Branch, New Jersey, United States
postcontent: Identical to the Model 1911 rifle in every way except for barrel and overall length, the Repeating Carbine, Model 1911 (K-11) replaced both the Model 1905 carbine and the Model 1889/1900 Short Rifle. Having been produced only 1/10 of an inch longer than the 1889/1900 Short Rifle, it was capable of firing the newer and more powerful GP1911 cartridge. The newer tangent sight was used on the carbine, but was graduated for the shorter barrel length.The Swiss at some point realized that its support troops, cavalry, and certain other units required a shorter rifle then what was currently available and so designed the Model 1911 Carbine. The Swiss 1911 Carbine being smaller, lighter and still lethally accurate, became a favorite of the Swiss Army and its popularity contributed to the design of its successor, the K31. They are also the last variation with the flatter mag plate which bench shooters tend to prefer, as well as the grooved Schmidt Rubin design bolt, and bakelite charging handle. Produced concurrently with the 1911 Rifle, the 1911 Carbine replaced both the Short Rifle and Calvary Carbine. While production of the 1911 rifle stopped in 1919, Carbine production continued until 1933 with some 184,000 Carbines being produced.My Schmidt-Rubin 1911 Carbine (K11) comes with a Waffenfabrik Neuhausen M1899 bayonet.  All serial numbers match and does not have import marks.  Serial # is 788xx out of 184,200 made which makes the production date in 1917.  Comes with original sling, cleaning kit, muzzle cap, hard case and 80 rounds of GP11.  It is in great shape for a 100 year old weapon.  I can provide more pictures upon request.

title: For Sale:  Scarce Winchester 1886 Extra Light Takedown 45-70
postcontent: The 1886 was another of John Browning's proof of genius, and the receiver of each gun starts out as a 40 ounce chunk of solid steel. It would handle the most powerful rounds of the era. After years of offering more and more powerful chamberings, gun makers then found ways to make them lighter. Fitted with a tapered 22 inch barrel, this rifle is a pleasure to tote and point. The special order takedown feature makes it even more practical. It takes down in about 10 seconds, and locks up tight just as fast. Made in the year of our Lord 1910, she is in good condition for 106 years old. The wood is about flush or over where it meets the steel, with only light carry marks. The stampings are very sharp and clear, indicating good care was given to this rifle. The bore is good, with some light roughness in the grooves, but plenty of shine and good rifling. The front sight is typical for a special order 1886, and is one of my favorites. It is the Lyman "hunting sight", which has matting and a real ivory bead. Let's look at value. I see 2 more of these listed over at guns international, a very nice one at 9000 and another with a climbin' Lyman for 7500. I will start this one for far less.Willing to ship

title: For Sale:  Scarce Winchester 1886 Extra Light Takedown 45-70
postcontent: The 1886 was another of John Browning's proof of genius, and the receiver of each gun starts out as a 40 ounce chunk of solid steel. It would handle the most powerful rounds of the era. After years of offering more and more powerful chamberings, gun makers then found ways to make them lighter. Fitted with a tapered 22 inch barrel, this rifle is a pleasure to tote and point. The special order takedown feature makes it even more practical. It takes down in about 10 seconds, and locks up tight just as fast. Made in the year of our Lord 1910, she is in good condition for 106 years old. The wood is about flush or over where it meets the steel, with only light carry marks. The stampings are very sharp and clear, indicating good care was given to this rifle. The bore is good, with some light roughness in the grooves, but plenty of shine and good rifling. The front sight is typical for a special order 1886, and is one of my favorites. It is the Lyman "hunting sight", which has matting and a real ivory bead. Let's look at value. I see 2 more of these listed over at guns international, a very nice one at 9000 and another with a climbin' Lyman for 7500. I will start this one for far less.Willing to ship
